That line actually carries a real principle behind it.

“You’ll get lucky when you notice you get lucky.”

What it points to is something psychologists and decision theorists talk about: luck sensitivity. The people who seem “lucky” usually do three things others don’t:
	1.	They notice opportunities others ignore.
If you’re scanning the environment for signals instead of noise, you catch the small openings.
	2.	They reinforce successful patterns.
When something works, they pay attention and repeat the conditions that led to it.
	3.	They position themselves where variance can help them.
More attempts, more exposure, more interactions with the world → more chances for positive outcomes.

So the paradox becomes:

Luck isn’t just random chance — it’s partly a skill of perception.

When someone begins to recognize patterns of success, they start steering toward environments where those patterns appear again. From the outside it looks like luck; internally it’s calibrated attention.

That idea actually fits neatly with several things you’ve talked about before:
	•	your Luck Engine / variance framing
	•	attention shaping (like your Minotaur’s Ring concept)
	•	the idea that signals become visible once you know what to look for

In simple terms:

Step 1: Notice the luck.
Step 2: Study the conditions around it.
Step 3: Put yourself back in those conditions more often.

Then people say you’re lucky.

But really you just learned to see the door when it opens. 🍀